WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:03.510
&gt;&gt; Announcer: From the Library
of Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:03.510 --> 00:00:22.510
[ Pause ]

00:00:22.510 --> 00:00:30.060
[ Applause ]

00:00:30.060 --> 00:00:33.710 position:56%
&gt;&gt; McLean: Thank you very, very much
for these luminous performances.

00:00:33.710 --> 00:00:35.880
It's been a tremendous
joy to have you

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:38.800
and the Bach Collegium Japan
here again at the Library,

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:42.140
and to have the time to share a
few of our treasures with you.

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:45.550
This afternoon we had the
pleasure of looking with you

00:00:45.550 --> 00:00:47.480
and your colleagues at
the original manuscript

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:51.390
of Bach's cantata number
ten, and your exhilaration

00:00:51.390 --> 00:00:56.270
at encountering this manuscript
was tremendously infectious.

00:00:56.270 --> 00:00:59.590
Can you talk a little about what
that means for you-the experience

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:03.460
of encountering an
original score like this.

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:09.470
&gt;&gt; Suzuki: Well-well, still
my heart is already beating

00:01:09.470 --> 00:01:13.730
so it's...I'll try to calm down.

00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:16.230
Well, all the time this-- -

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:19.310
we have seen a wonderful
original autograph this afternoon.

00:01:19.310 --> 00:01:22.940
Those original manuscripts,
especially autographs

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:31.220
of Johann Sebastian Bach
himself, inspires us very much,

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:37.160
because he has written not only
the notes but sometimes slurs,

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:38.460
indications of articulations,

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:42.190
and so on-all the details are
very, very interesting to see.

00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:47.340
You can never sense
these kinds of things

00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:50.160 position:56%
from the printed material of course.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:53.540
So, of course the Neue Bach
Ausgabe-that's a new Bach

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:59.140
edition-helps us a lot, but still
we should [at] all time trace

00:01:59.140 --> 00:02:04.500
to-actually anything
procedural-from the original source

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:07.690
until the material,
the printed and so on.

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:10.920
So this is a really
great pleasure, yea.

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:13.250
&gt;&gt; McLean: You know, there was
a little phrase at the bottom

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:17.050
of the page that you noticed-at the
very bottom underneath the staves.

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:18.350
Tell the audience about that.

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:21.410
&gt;&gt; Suzuki: Yea, that's
very interesting.

00:02:21.410 --> 00:02:30.730
Here is one of the most important
materials of the cantata number 10,

00:02:30.730 --> 00:02:36.930
"Meine Seel erhebt den Herrn"-this
is the German magnificat,

00:02:36.930 --> 00:02:38.230
and the [inaudible] score.

00:02:38.230 --> 00:02:41.330
And, on the edge of the
first page Bach has written

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:46.140
down a couple bars
right next to that page

00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:51.930
that means...the one thing
probably he has made an attempt how

00:02:51.930 --> 00:02:55.240
to the polyphonic line
works out and so on.

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:58.100
But at the same time
when he has finished

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.390
with the first page probably he
could not turn [the page] over yet,

00:03:01.390 --> 00:03:02.880
because the ink is still wet.

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:05.710
So that's why before he
forgets the next couple

00:03:05.710 --> 00:03:08.180
of bars he has written
down on the edge.

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:09.980 position:56%
So that's really interesting things.

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:14.220
[ Laughter ]

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:17.180
&gt;&gt; McLean: And you said that's
very rare...you hadn't seen that...

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:18.480
&gt;&gt; Suzuki: Yes, very, very rare.

00:03:18.480 --> 00:03:19.780
&gt;&gt; McLean: This is the kind
of thing that you learn

00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:21.510
when you're looking at these.

00:03:21.510 --> 00:03:24.610
And you mentioned that the
parts are actually more valuable

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:27.080
for a performer than the score.

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:32.240
&gt;&gt; Suzuki: Well actually,
at the time no big machine

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:37.480
so the parts must be
made from the score.

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:41.320
So, probably at that time the set

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:46.480
of parts...performing parts is
more important than the score,

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:54.210
because if you get the parts
then you can immediately perform

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:55.510
the piece.

00:03:55.510 --> 00:03:58.970
So, that's why when
the...after his death

00:03:58.970 --> 00:04:05.190
in 1750 all the original material,
Bach himself, divided in two.

00:04:05.190 --> 00:04:07.230
In one is the score and some duets,

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:10.870
and the other group
is the set of parts.

00:04:10.870 --> 00:04:13.860
This set of parts [is]
thought probably more valuable

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:17.040
than the score.

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:18.840
&gt;&gt; McLean: And you mentioned
that one half would go

00:04:18.840 --> 00:04:20.140
to his family and others...

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:21.440
&gt;&gt; Suzuki: Yes.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:25.000
One score and duet going
to one part/ person

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.570
and the other sets going
[to the] second person.

00:04:29.570 --> 00:04:33.130
Bach has written down in principal
all the detail articulations

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:38.570
and indications of slurs,
and so on-not in the score,

00:04:38.570 --> 00:04:42.640
instead they're only
in the parts directly.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:45.610
On the parts [are] all
the notes what could be

00:04:45.610 --> 00:04:49.110
by [Bach's] copyist-his
assistant or sons and so on.

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:55.980 position:56%
But, after that he has always looked
through and checked all the details.

00:04:55.980 --> 00:05:00.830
At the same time he has added
many indications of slurs

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:04.220
and also figuration[s]
of the basso continuo.

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:09.110
So, on the parts the notes are
usually copied by someone else,

00:05:09.110 --> 00:05:14.830
but all the detail indications
are by [Bach] himself.

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:17.360
&gt;&gt; McLean: It was a
wonderful, wonderful time.

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:20.290
Critics talk about-- - of
course write about you-- -

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:23.680
your performances as
impeccable, revelatory,

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:26.990
and imbued with spiritual
rigor, and if we had time

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:29.060
