we could talk

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:32.040
about how you inculcate
these kinds of qualities

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:34.750
in teaching-in your students.

00:05:34.750 --> 00:05:37.250
So, we don't really have time
for that, but I was wondering

00:05:37.250 --> 00:05:40.220
if you'd comment on some
of the remarks you've made

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:43.050
about the technique end of things.

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:49.050
And you say that you suggested
that people think theatrically.

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:53.990
&gt;&gt; Suzuki: Yea, someone said
that life is the theater.

00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:59.260
Bach's music is so
dramatic and I think

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:02.870
that all the technical aspects
go together with the idea

00:06:02.870 --> 00:06:07.790
of the music-not only
music, but the expression.

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:11.910
So techniques are always developed
by this kind of idea, musical idea,

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:17.610
and then how...it's very important
to get a musical idea or what kind

00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:20.340
of expression you want to make.

00:06:20.340 --> 00:06:23.400
That makes the technique better.

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:27.070
So, those two things
always go together.

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:31.430
At that time, for example, he has
published a couple of collections

00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:34.460 position:56%
of harpsichord pieces called...under
the title of "Clavier-Übung."

00:06:34.460 --> 00:06:41.440
Clavier-Übung means
actually "for practice."

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:42.740
Clavier-Übung is the practice.

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:45.310
So at that time the practice meant

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:51.860
for probably...to get an
idea to...to become able

00:06:51.860 --> 00:06:53.780
to make a...this and
that expression.

00:06:53.780 --> 00:06:59.080
So, it's not only the
moving fingers and so on.

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:03.200
In the Baroque time
this kind of motion

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:07.680 position:56%
of the fingers [was] always
closely connected to the expression.

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:11.150
So probably after the
Czerny or Beethoven time,

00:07:11.150 --> 00:07:13.810
you see the piano technique[s]
are more developed,

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:21.020
and probably it was needed to be
trained a little more mechanically.

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:25.030
So that's why, for example,
etudes of Czerny and so on,

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:28.900
is completely different
ideas-certain concepts

00:07:28.900 --> 00:07:30.200
from the Baroque time.

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:31.910
Baroque time is still...everything
was very well related together.

00:07:31.910 --> 00:07:33.210
&gt;&gt; McLean: Fascinating.

00:07:33.210 --> 00:07:35.350
Well we...maybe a question
